Homework 1-2: Introduction to Webscraping with BeautifulSoup¶

Sometimes the most interesting data sets dont come with an API or pre-packaged plain-text CSVs. In these situations, web scraping can be a powerful tool, enabling us to extract and convert data from almost any format found on the internet into a tabular form we can conduct further analysis on.

For this section we will be working with historic population estimates of different US states listed on Wikipedia here:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_U.S._states_by_historical_population. In this section, youll learn how to import html-tables on the web into something you can manipulate with pandas.

Specifically, we will:

1. Download the relevant webpage as raw html with the requests library  
2. Parse the html into a tree-like python-object with the BeautifulSoup library
3. Use BeautifulSoup to select and extract just the tables were interested in
4. Combine the tables, clean the text, and convert them into a single python dictionary 
5. Make a pandas dataframe from the dictionary 
6. Doing some basic analysis and plotting (with matplotlib)

As usual, our first step is to import the necessary libraries.

In [1]:
import numpy as np
import scipy as sp
import matplotlib as mpl
import matplotlib.cm as cm
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd
pd.set_option('display.width', 500)
pd.set_option('display.max_columns', 100)
pd.set_option('display.notebook_repr_html', True)
import seaborn as sns
sns.set_style("whitegrid")
sns.set_context("poster")

# Two new 
import requests 
requests.packages.urllib3.disable_warnings()
#Requests enables us to download raw html as text
from bs4 import BeautifulSoup 
# BeautifulSoup enables us to navigate html in python with dom-like tree structure

Step 1: Download the relevant webpage as raw html¶

In [2]:
#url = "http://www.baidu.com"
url="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_U.S._states_by_historical_population"

r = requests.get(url, timeout=60,verify=False)

Always remember to not to be evil when scraping with requests! If downloading multiple pages, always put a delay between requests (e.g,, time.sleep(1), with the time library) so you dont unwittingly hammer someones webserver and/or get blocked.

In [3]:
raw_html = r.text
raw_html
print(raw_html)

<p>This is a <b>list of U.S. states and territories by historical population</b>, as enumerated every decade by the <a href="/wiki/United_States_Census" class="mw-redirect" title="United States Census">United States Census</a>. As required by the <a href="/wiki/United_States_Constitution" class="mw-redirect" title="United States Constitution">United States Constitution</a>, a census has been conducted every 10 years since 1790. Although the decennial census collects a variety of information that has been used in demographic studies, marketing, and other enterprises, the purpose of the census as stated in the Constitution is to produce an "actual enumeration" of the number of persons in the states in order to calculate their <a href="/wiki/United_States_congressional_apportionment" title="United States congressional apportionment">Congressional apportionment</a>.
</p><p>As the United States has grown in area and population, new states have been formed out of U.S. territories or the division of existing states. <i><b>The population figures provided here reflect modern state boundaries</b></i>. Shaded areas of the tables indicate census years when a territory or the part of another state had not yet been admitted as a new state.<sup id="cite_ref-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-1">&#91;a&#93;</a></sup> Since 1920, the "total population" of the United States has been considered the population of all the States and the District of Columbia; territories and other possessions were counted as additional population.<sup id="cite_ref-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-2">&#91;b&#93;</a></sup> As of 2021<sup class="plainlinks noexcerpt noprint asof-tag update" style="display:none;"><a class="external text" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=List_of_U.S._states_and_territories_by_historical_population&amp;action=edit">&#91;update&#93;</a></sup>, five U.S. territories (<a href="/wiki/American_Samoa" title="American Samoa">American Samoa</a>, <a href="/wiki/Guam" title="Guam">Guam</a>, the <a href="/wiki/Northern_Mariana_Islands" title="Northern Mariana Islands">Northern Mariana Islands</a>, <a href="/wiki/Puerto_Rico" title="Puerto Rico">Puerto Rico</a> and the <a href="/wiki/U.S._Virgin_Islands" class="mw-redirect" title="U.S. Virgin Islands">U.S. Virgin Islands</a>), along with the <a href="/wiki/U.S._Minor_Outlying_Islands" class="mw-redirect" title="U.S. Minor Outlying Islands">U.S. Minor Outlying Islands</a>, are not included in the count of total U.S. population.
</p>
<meta property="mw:PageProp/toc" />
<h2><span id="1790.E2.80.931860.2C_census_data"></span><span class="mw-headline" id="17901860,_census_data">17901860, census data</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=List_of_U.S._states_and_territories_by_historical_population&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1" title="Edit section: 17901860, census data"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<h3><span id="Total_population.2C_1790.E2.80.931860"></span><span class="mw-headline" id="Total_population,_17901860">Total population, 17901860</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=List_of_U.S._states_and_territories_by_historical_population&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2" title="Edit section: Total population, 17901860"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>Total population counts for the Censuses of 1790 through 1860 include both free and enslaved persons. Native Americans were not identified in the Census of 1790 through 1840 and only sporadically from 1850 until 1890, if they lived outside of Indian Territory or off reservations. Beginning with the 1900 census, Native Americans were fully enumerated along with the general population.<sup id="cite_ref-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-3">&#91;c&#93;</a></sup>
</p>

<h2><span id="Minor_Outlying_Islands_population.2C_1910.E2.80.932000.2C_census_data"></span><span class="mw-headline" id="Minor_Outlying_Islands_population,_19102000,_census_data">Minor Outlying Islands population, 19102000, census data</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=List_of_U.S._states_and_territories_by_historical_population&amp;action=edit&amp;section=6" title="Edit section: Minor Outlying Islands population, 19102000, census data"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<p>Several small island territories are included in the U.S. Census Bureau's Island Areas region as <a href="/wiki/U.S._Minor_Outlying_Islands" class="mw-redirect" title="U.S. Minor Outlying Islands">U.S. Minor Outlying Islands</a>. These mostly lack permanent residents, but have been included in some census counts since 1910. Prior to 1959, most of the Pacific minor island territories were enumerated with the Hawaii Territory, but not included in the territory's population count. Minor Outlying Islands that have never had a population enumerated by the U.S. Census Bureau are not included. Since 2000, the U.S. Census Bureau has not reported data for the Minor Outlying Islands as part of its standard data products.
</p>

<h2><span id="U.S._federally_affiliated_overseas_population.2C_1900.E2.80.932020.2C_census_data"></span><span class="mw-headline" id="U.S._federally_affiliated_overseas_population,_19002020,_census_data">U.S. federally affiliated overseas population, 19002020, census data</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=List_of_U.S._states_and_territories_by_historical_population&amp;action=edit&amp;section=7" title="Edit section: U.S. federally affiliated overseas population, 19002020, census data"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<p>Since 1900, the U.S. Census Bureau has worked to count Americans living overseas, including those soldiers and sailors overseas, merchants on vessels at sea, and diplomats. (Counts were also provided in the 1830 and 1840 Censuses.) Attempts to count private citizens have been made, too, but with only minimal success.<sup id="cite_ref-39" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-39">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> In 1970 and since 1990, the "U.S. Federally Affiliated Overseas Population"  essentially citizens serving in military, diplomatic, and other federal agency postings overseas  have been counted based upon federal records. For the purpose of apportionment, they are assigned to their on-record home state. Figures prior to 2000 are from <i>Americans Overseas in U.S. Censuses</i>.<sup id="cite_ref-40" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-40">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> Data for 2000 and 2010 is from a 2012 Census assessment report,<sup id="cite_ref-41" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-41">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup> and 2020 data is from that year's Census.<sup id="cite_ref-42" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-42">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup>
</p>

<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Notes">Notes</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=List_of_U.S._states_and_territories_by_historical_population&amp;action=edit&amp;section=12" title="Edit section: Notes"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1011085734"><div class="reflist reflist-lower-alpha">
<div class="mw-references-wrap mw-references-columns"><ol class="references">
<li id="cite_note-1"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-1">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">The <a href="/wiki/District_of_Columbia" class="mw-redirect" title="District of Columbia">District of Columbia</a> is not shaded.</span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-2"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-2">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Prior to 1920, territories in the <a href="/wiki/Continental_United_States" class="mw-redirect" title="Continental United States">continental United States</a> were generally included in the total population figure, but more far-flung territories were not.</span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-3"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-3">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1133582631"><cite class="citation web cs1"><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://www.archives.gov/research/census/native-americans/1790-1930.htm">"American Indians in the Federal Decennial Census, 1790-1930"</a>. U.S. Census Bureau<span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved <span class="nowrap">August 27,</span> 2021</span>.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.btitle=American+Indians+in+the+Federal+Decennial+Census%2C+1790-1930&amp;rft.pub=U.S.+Census+Bureau&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.archives.gov%2Fresearch%2Fcensus%2Fnative-americans%2F1790-1930.htm&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AList+of+U.S.+states+and+territories+by+historical+population" class="Z3988"></span> </span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-date-4"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-date_4-0">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Dates for the states are the dates they were admitted to the Union. Dates for the territories are the dates they were acquired by the United States (shown in italics). Date for the District of Columbia is the date the district was formed.</span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-5"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-5">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">The District of Columbia is not a state, but was created through the <a href="/wiki/Residence_Act" title="Residence Act">Residence Act</a> of 1790 from territory donated by Maryland and Virginia; however, the Virginia portion was <a href="/wiki/District_of_Columbia_retrocession" title="District of Columbia retrocession">retroceded</a> to the state in 1846.</span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-6"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-6">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Previously a part of the <a href="/wiki/Orleans_Territory" class="mw-redirect" title="Orleans Territory">Orleans Territory</a>.</span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-7"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-7">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Between 1790 and 1820, the <a href="/wiki/District_of_Maine" title="District of Maine">District of Maine</a> was part of the state of Massachusetts.</span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-8"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-8">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Starting with the 1800 Census, Maryland donated territory to create the District of Columbia.</span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-9"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-9">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Figures recorded for <a href="/wiki/Dakota_Territory" title="Dakota Territory">Dakota Territory</a> by the censuses of 1860, 1870, and 1880 are listed here as belonging to South Dakota.</span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-10"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-10">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Vermont was enumerated in the 1790 Census but was only admitted as a state in 1791.</span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-11"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-11">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Between 1790 and 1860, the state of West Virginia was part of Virginia. In addition, between the Censuses of 1800 and 1840, territory donated by the state of Virginia formed a portion of District of Columbia, but the land was returned in 1846.</span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-12"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-12">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Between 1790 and 1860, the state of West Virginia was part of Virginia; the data for each state reflect the present-day boundaries.</span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-13"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-13">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Not including the Virginia counties that formed the new state of West Virginia in 1863, but includes the enslaved population in the returned land that had been donated to form the District of Columbia.</span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-14"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-14">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">These figures are for the Virginia counties that formed the state of West Virginia in 1863.</span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-15"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-15">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Figures include people on <a href="/wiki/Native_Americans_in_the_United_States" title="Native Americans in the United States">Native American</a> reservations in the United States not otherwise enumerated.</span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-16"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-16">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">From 1930 onward the reported value includes <a href="/wiki/Swains_Island" title="Swains Island">Swains Island</a>, which was incorporated into American Samoa in 1925</span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-17"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-17">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">From 1910 to 1940, <a href="/wiki/U.S._Minor_Outlying_Islands" class="mw-redirect" title="U.S. Minor Outlying Islands">U.S. Minor Outlying Islands</a> in the Pacific were enumerated with the Hawaii Territory by the U.S. Census bureau. The values here exclude those island populations not incorporated into the state of Hawai&#x2bb;i. (per <link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1133582631"><cite class="citation report cs1"><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://www.census.gov/geographies/reference-files/2010/geo/state-local-geo-guides-2010/hawaii.html">Guide to 2010 State and Local Census Geography: Hawaii</a> (Report). Washington, D.C.: U.S. Census Bureau<span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved <span class="nowrap">August 24,</span> 2021</span>.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=report&amp;rft.btitle=Guide+to+2010+State+and+Local+Census+Geography%3A+Hawaii&amp;rft.place=Washington%2C+D.C.&amp;rft.pub=U.S.+Census+Bureau&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.census.gov%2Fgeographies%2Freference-files%2F2010%2Fgeo%2Fstate-local-geo-guides-2010%2Fhawaii.html&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AList+of+U.S.+states+and+territories+by+historical+population" class="Z3988"></span>)</span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-Midway-18"><span class="mw-cite-backlink">^ <a href="#cite_ref-Midway_18-0"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-Midway_18-1"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-Midway_18-2"><sup><i><b>c</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class="reference-text">Total excludes counts for Midway Atoll</span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-19"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-19">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Total excludes counts for Baker, Canton, Enderbury, Howland, and Jarvis islands and Johnston, Midway, Palmyra, and Wake atolls.</span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-20"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-20">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">The 1890 and 1900 figures are the combined total for the <a href="/wiki/Oklahoma_Territory" title="Oklahoma Territory">Oklahoma Territory</a> and <a href="/wiki/Indian_Territory" title="Indian Territory">Indian Territory</a>, which were combined when Oklahoma became a state in 1907 (per <link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1133582631"><cite class="citation book cs1"><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://www2.census.gov/prod2/decennial/documents/1907pop_OK-IndianTerritory.pdf"><i>Census Bulletin 89: Population of Oklahoma and Indian Territory</i></a> <span class="cs1-format">(PDF)</span>. Washington, D.C.: Government Printing Office. 1907<span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved <span class="nowrap">September 30,</span> 2020</span>.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Census+Bulletin+89%3A+Population+of+Oklahoma+and+Indian+Territory&amp;rft.place=Washington%2C+D.C.&amp;rft.pub=Government+Printing+Office&amp;rft.date=1907&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fwww2.census.gov%2Fprod2%2Fdecennial%2Fdocuments%2F1907pop_OK-IndianTerritory.pdf&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AList+of+U.S.+states+and+territories+by+historical+population" class="Z3988"></span>). The 1900 figures include <a href="/wiki/Greer_County,_Texas" title="Greer County, Texas">Greer County</a>, which previously had been claimed by Texas.</span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-21"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-21">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Oklahoma Territory population 78,475; Indian Territory population 180,182.</span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-22"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-22">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Oklahoma Territory population 398,331; Indian Territory population 392,060.</span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-USC1940-23"><span class="mw-cite-backlink">^ <a href="#cite_ref-USC1940_23-0"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-USC1940_23-1"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-USC1940_23-2"><sup><i><b>c</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class="reference-text">Extrapolated value reported in 1940 Census</span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-noAK-24"><span class="mw-cite-backlink">^ <a href="#cite_ref-noAK_24-0"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-noAK_24-1"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class="reference-text">Total excludes population of Alaska</span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-25"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-25">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Total for 1890 includes 62,622,250 persons enumerated in the states and territories, plus 325,464 persons in Indian Territory and on reservations not otherwise counted.</span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-26"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-26">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Total excludes population of Alaska and Hawaii</span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-27"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-27">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Total excludes population of Alaska, Guam, Hawaii, Puerto Rico, and U.S. Minor Outlying Islands</span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-AKASGUHICZPHPRVI-28"><span class="mw-cite-backlink">^ <a href="#cite_ref-AKASGUHICZPHPRVI_28-0"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-AKASGUHICZPHPRVI_28-1"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-AKASGUHICZPHPRVI_28-2"><sup><i><b>c</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class="reference-text">Total excludes population of Alaska, American Samoa, Guam, Hawaii, Panama Canal Zone, the Philippines, Puerto Rico, U.S. Virgin Islands, and U.S. Minor Outlying Islands</span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-AKASGUHICZPRVI-29"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-AKASGUHICZPRVI_29-0">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Total excludes population of Alaska, American Samoa, Guam, Hawaii, Panama Canal Zone, Puerto Rico, U.S. Virgin Islands, and U.S. Minor Outlying Islands</span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-30"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-30">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Figures recorded as part of the Pacific Trust Territories by the census of 1970 are listed here as belonging to the Northern Mariana Islands.</span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-1958PTT-31"><span class="mw-cite-backlink">^ <a href="#cite_ref-1958PTT_31-0"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-1958PTT_31-1"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-1958PTT_31-2"><sup><i><b>c</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class="reference-text">From <i>Census of the Trust Territory of the Pacific Islands 1958</i>, which the 1960 Census used for reporting total population of the Pacific Trust Territory</span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-32"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-32">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Total excludes population of American Samoa, Guam, Panama Canal Zone, Puerto Rico, U.S. Virgin Islands, and U.S. Minor Outlying Islands</span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-33"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-33">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Total excludes population of American Samoa, Guam, Northern Mariana Islands, Pacific Trust Territory, Palau, Panama Canal Zone, Puerto Rico, U.S. Virgin Islands, and U.S. Minor Outlying Islands</span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-34"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-34">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Total excludes population of American Samoa, Guam, Northern Mariana Islands, Pacific Trust Territory, Palau, Puerto Rico, U.S. Virgin Islands, and U.S. Minor Outlying Islands</span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-35"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-35">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Total excludes population of American Samoa, Guam, Northern Mariana Islands, Palau, Puerto Rico, U.S. Virgin Islands, and U.S. Minor Outlying Islands</span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-ASGUMPPRVI-36"><span class="mw-cite-backlink">^ <a href="#cite_ref-ASGUMPPRVI_36-0"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-ASGUMPPRVI_36-1"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-ASGUMPPRVI_36-2"><sup><i><b>c</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class="reference-text">Total excludes population of American Samoa, Guam, Northern Mariana Islands, Puerto Rico, U.S. Virgin Islands, and U.S. Minor Outlying Islands</span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-37"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-37">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">3 people each on Baker and Jarvis; 4 people on Howland</span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-38"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-38">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Part of the Hawaii Territory prior to 1959; remained a separate territory after Hawai&#x2bb;i gained statehood.</span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-former-43"><span class="mw-cite-backlink">^ <a href="#cite_ref-former_43-0"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-former_43-1"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-former_43-2"><sup><i><b>c</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-former_43-3"><sup><i><b>d</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-former_43-4"><sup><i><b>e</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-former_43-5"><sup><i><b>f</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-former_43-6"><sup><i><b>g</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class="reference-text">This territory no longer exists.</span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-44"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-44">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Relinquished to <a href="/wiki/Kiribati" title="Kiribati">Kiribati</a> in 1979.</span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-45"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-45">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">4 people on Enderbury; 44 people on Canton</span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-Enderbury-46"><span class="mw-cite-backlink">^ <a href="#cite_ref-Enderbury_46-0"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-Enderbury_46-1"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class="reference-text">All on Canton; Enderbury reported no inhabitants</span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-47"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-47">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Population figures provided to U.S. Census Bureau by the government of Nicaragua.</span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-48"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-48">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Leased from Nicaragua for 99 years, but lease terminated in 1970</span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-49"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-49">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Excludes counts for Northern Mariana Islands and Palau.</span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-50"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-50">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">The trusteeship was ended in 1986.</span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-51"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-51">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Figures recorded as part of the Pacific Trust Territories by the census of 1970 and 1980 are listed here as belonging to Palau.</span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-52"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-52">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">The Republic of Palau became independent from the United States in 1994.</span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-PCZ-53"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-PCZ_53-0">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">The territory was abolished in 1979.</span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-54"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-54">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">The Census Bureau never formally enumerated the Philippine Islands when they were a U.S. territorial possession; however, the 1940 Census included data from the <a href="/wiki/Census_in_the_Philippines" title="Census in the Philippines">1939 Census</a> of the <a href="/wiki/Commonwealth_of_the_Philippines" title="Commonwealth of the Philippines">Commonwealth of the Philippines</a>, including extrapolated population figures for 1930 and 1920.</span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-55"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-55">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">The United States officially recognized Philippine independence in 1946</span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-56"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-56">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">In 1971, the United States relinquished its claim to the islands, allowing Hondorus to take full control of them.</span>
</li>

Now, we have all our data in the notebook. Unfortunately, it is the form of one really long string, which is hard to work with directly. This is where BeautifulSoup comes in.

Step 2: Parse the html with BeautifulSoup¶

In [4]:
soup = BeautifulSoup(raw_html, 'html.parser')

Key BeautifulSoup functions well be using in this section:

  • soup.prettify(): Returns cleanedup version of raw html for printing
  • soup.find_all(,attrs=): Returns python list of matching objects
  • soup.find(,attrs=): Returns first matching object
  • soup.text/soup.get_text(): Returns visible text of an object (e.g.,"<p>Some text</p>" -> "Some text")

BeautifulSoup is a very powerful library -- much more info here: https://www.crummy.com/software/BeautifulSoup/bs4/doc/

Let's practice some BeautifulSoup commands..¶

Print a cleanedup version of raw html for printing

In [5]:
# Your code here  
print(soup.prettify())

      <div aria-labelledby="firstHeading" class="vector-body" data-mw-ve-target-container="" id="bodyContent">
       <div class="vector-body-before-content">
        <div class="mw-indicators">
        </div>
        <div class="noprint" id="siteSub">
         From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia
        </div>
       </div>
       <div id="contentSub">
        <div id="mw-content-subtitle">
         <span class="mw-redirectedfrom">
          (Redirected from
          <a class="mw-redirect" href="/w/index.php?title=List_of_U.S._states_by_historical_population&amp;redirect=no" title="List of U.S. states by historical population">
           List of U.S. states by historical population
          </a>
          )
         </span>
        </div>
       </div>
       <div class="mw-body-content" id="mw-content-text">
        <div class="mw-content-ltr mw-parser-output" dir="ltr" lang="en">
         <p class="mw-empty-elt">
         </p>
         <figure typeof="mw:File/Thumb">
          <a class="mw-file-description" href="/wiki/File:USpopgrowth1970-2020.svg">
           <img class="mw-file-element" data-file-height="593" data-file-width="959" decoding="async" height="263" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/68/USpopgrowth1970-2020.svg/425px-USpopgrowth1970-2020.svg.png" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/68/USpopgrowth1970-2020.svg/638px-USpopgrowth1970-2020.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/68/USpopgrowth1970-2020.svg/850px-USpopgrowth1970-2020.svg.png 2x" width="425"/>
          </a>
          <figcaption>
           The population growth of each
           <a href="/wiki/U.S._state" title="U.S. state">
            U.S. state
           </a>
           from 1970 to 2020.
           <style data-mw-deduplicate="TemplateStyles:r981673959">
            .mw-parser-output .legend{page-break-inside:avoid;break-inside:avoid-column}.mw-parser-output .legend-color{display:inline-block;min-width:1.25em;height:1.25em;line-height:1.25;margin:1px 0;text-align:center;border:1px solid black;background-color:transparent;color:black}.mw-parser-output .legend-text{}
           </style>
           <div class="legend">
            <span class="legend-color mw-no-invert" style="background-color:#ff339c; color:black;">
            </span>
            Population decline
           </div>
           <link href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r981673959" rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style"/>
           <div class="legend">
            <span class="legend-color mw-no-invert" style="background-color:#ABEBC6; color:black;">
            </span>
            Population growth of less than 24.99%
           </div>
           <link href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r981673959" rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style"/>
           <div class="legend">
            <span class="legend-color mw-no-invert" style="background-color:#58D68D; color:black;">
            </span>
            Population growth of less than 49.99%
           </div>
           <link href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r981673959" rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style"/>
           <div class="legend">
            <span class="legend-color mw-no-invert" style="background-color:#2ECC71; color:black;">
            </span>
            Population growth of less than 99.99%
           </div>
           <link href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r981673959" rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style"/>
           <div class="legend">
            <span class="legend-color mw-no-invert" style="background-color:#28B463; color:black;">
            </span>
            Population growth of less than 149.99%
           </div>
           <link href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r981673959" rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style"/>
           <div class="legend">
            <span class="legend-color mw-no-invert" style="background-color:#239B56; color:black;">
            </span>
            Population growth of less than 199.99%
           </div>
           <link href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r981673959" rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style"/>
           <div class="legend">
            <span class="legend-color mw-no-invert" style="background-color:#186A3B; color:white;">
            </span>
            Population growth of more than 200.00%
           </div>
          </figcaption>
         </figure>
         <p>
          This is a
          <b>
           list of U.S. states and territories by historical population
          </b>
          , as enumerated every decade by the
          <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/United_States_Census" title="United States Census">
           United States Census
          </a>
          . As required by the
          <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/United_States_Constitution" title="United States Constitution">
           United States Constitution
          </a>
          , a census has been conducted every 10 years since 1790. Although the decennial census collects a variety of information that has been used in demographic studies, marketing, and other enterprises, the purpose of the census as stated in the Constitution is to produce an "actual enumeration" of the number of persons in the states in order to calculate their
          <a href="/wiki/United_States_congressional_apportionment" title="United States congressional apportionment">
           Congressional apportionment
          </a>
          .
         </p>
         <p>
          As the United States has grown in area and population, new states have been formed out of U.S. territories or the division of existing states.
          <i>
           <b>
            The population figures provided here reflect modern state boundaries
           </b>
          </i>
          . Shaded areas of the tables indicate census years when a territory or the part of another state had not yet been admitted as a new state.
          <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-1">
           <a href="#cite_note-1">
            [a]
           </a>
          </sup>
          Since 1920, the "total population" of the United States has been considered the population of all the States and the District of Columbia; territories and other possessions were counted as additional population.
          <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-2">
           <a href="#cite_note-2">
            [b]
           </a>
          </sup>
          As of 2021
          <sup class="plainlinks noexcerpt noprint asof-tag update" style="display:none;">
           <a class="external text" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=List_of_U.S._states_and_territories_by_historical_population&amp;action=edit">
            [update]
           </a>
          </sup>
          , five U.S. territories (
          <a href="/wiki/American_Samoa" title="American Samoa">
           American Samoa
          </a>
          ,
          <a href="/wiki/Guam" title="Guam">
           Guam
          </a>
          , the
          <a href="/wiki/Northern_Mariana_Islands" title="Northern Mariana Islands">
           Northern Mariana Islands
          </a>
          ,
          <a href="/wiki/Puerto_Rico" title="Puerto Rico">
           Puerto Rico
          </a>
          and the
          <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/U.S._Virgin_Islands" title="U.S. Virgin Islands">
           U.S. Virgin Islands
          </a>
          ), along with the
          <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/U.S._Minor_Outlying_Islands" title="U.S. Minor Outlying Islands">
           U.S. Minor Outlying Islands
          </a>
          , are not included in the count of total U.S. population.
         </p>
         <meta property="mw:PageProp/toc">
          <h2>
           <span id="1790.E2.80.931860.2C_census_data">
           </span>
           <span class="mw-headline" id="17901860,_census_data">
            17901860, census data
           </span>
           <span class="mw-editsection">
            <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
             [
            </span>
            <a href="/w/index.php?title=List_of_U.S._states_and_territories_by_historical_population&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1" title="Edit section: 17901860, census data">
             <span>
              edit
             </span>
            </a>
            <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
             ]
            </span>
           </span>
          </h2>
          <h3>
           <span id="Total_population.2C_1790.E2.80.931860">
           </span>
           <span class="mw-headline" id="Total_population,_17901860">
            Total population, 17901860
           </span>
           <span class="mw-editsection">
            <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
             [
            </span>
            <a href="/w/index.php?title=List_of_U.S._states_and_territories_by_historical_population&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2" title="Edit section: Total population, 17901860">
             <span>
              edit
             </span>
            </a>
            <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
             ]
            </span>
           </span>
          </h3>
          <p>
           Total population counts for the Censuses of 1790 through 1860 include both free and enslaved persons. Native Americans were not identified in the Census of 1790 through 1840 and only sporadically from 1850 until 1890, if they lived outside of Indian Territory or off reservations. Beginning with the 1900 census, Native Americans were fully enumerated along with the general population.
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-3">
            <a href="#cite_note-3">
             [c]
            </a>
           </sup>
          </p>

          <h2>
           <span id="Minor_Outlying_Islands_population.2C_1910.E2.80.932000.2C_census_data">
           </span>
           <span class="mw-headline" id="Minor_Outlying_Islands_population,_19102000,_census_data">
            Minor Outlying Islands population, 19102000, census data
           </span>
           <span class="mw-editsection">
            <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
             [
            </span>
            <a href="/w/index.php?title=List_of_U.S._states_and_territories_by_historical_population&amp;action=edit&amp;section=6" title="Edit section: Minor Outlying Islands population, 19102000, census data">
             <span>
              edit
             </span>
            </a>
            <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
             ]
            </span>
           </span>
          </h2>
          <p>
           Several small island territories are included in the U.S. Census Bureau's Island Areas region as
           <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/U.S._Minor_Outlying_Islands" title="U.S. Minor Outlying Islands">
            U.S. Minor Outlying Islands
           </a>
           . These mostly lack permanent residents, but have been included in some census counts since 1910. Prior to 1959, most of the Pacific minor island territories were enumerated with the Hawaii Territory, but not included in the territory's population count. Minor Outlying Islands that have never had a population enumerated by the U.S. Census Bureau are not included. Since 2000, the U.S. Census Bureau has not reported data for the Minor Outlying Islands as part of its standard data products.
          </p>

          <h2>
           <span id="U.S._federally_affiliated_overseas_population.2C_1900.E2.80.932020.2C_census_data">
           </span>
           <span class="mw-headline" id="U.S._federally_affiliated_overseas_population,_19002020,_census_data">
            U.S. federally affiliated overseas population, 19002020, census data
           </span>
           <span class="mw-editsection">
            <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
             [
            </span>
            <a href="/w/index.php?title=List_of_U.S._states_and_territories_by_historical_population&amp;action=edit&amp;section=7" title="Edit section: U.S. federally affiliated overseas population, 19002020, census data">
             <span>
              edit
             </span>
            </a>
            <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
             ]
            </span>
           </span>
          </h2>
          <p>
           Since 1900, the U.S. Census Bureau has worked to count Americans living overseas, including those soldiers and sailors overseas, merchants on vessels at sea, and diplomats. (Counts were also provided in the 1830 and 1840 Censuses.) Attempts to count private citizens have been made, too, but with only minimal success.
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-39">
            <a href="#cite_note-39">
             [1]
            </a>
           </sup>
           In 1970 and since 1990, the "U.S. Federally Affiliated Overseas Population"  essentially citizens serving in military, diplomatic, and other federal agency postings overseas  have been counted based upon federal records. For the purpose of apportionment, they are assigned to their on-record home state. Figures prior to 2000 are from
           <i>
            Americans Overseas in U.S. Censuses
           </i>
           .
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-40">
            <a href="#cite_note-40">
             [2]
            </a>
           </sup>
           Data for 2000 and 2010 is from a 2012 Census assessment report,
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-41">
            <a href="#cite_note-41">
             [3]
            </a>
           </sup>
           and 2020 data is from that year's Census.
           <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-42">
            <a href="#cite_note-42">
             [4]
            </a>
           </sup>
          </p>
          <table class="wikitable" style="text-align:right;">
           <tbody>
            <tr>

          <h2>
           <span id="Former_territories.2C_1920.E2.80.931990.2C_census_data">
           </span>
           <span class="mw-headline" id="Former_territories,_19201990,_census_data">
            Former territories, 19201990, census data
           </span>
           <span class="mw-editsection">
            <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
             [
            </span>
            <a href="/w/index.php?title=List_of_U.S._states_and_territories_by_historical_population&amp;action=edit&amp;section=8" title="Edit section: Former territories, 19201990, census data">
             <span>

            </a>

          <h2>
           <span id="1900.E2.80.932022.2C_Federal_Reserve_economic_data">
           </span>
           <span class="mw-headline" id="19002022,_Federal_Reserve_economic_data">
            19002022, Federal Reserve economic data
           </span>
           <span class="mw-editsection">
            <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
             [
            </span>
            <a href="/w/index.php?title=List_of_U.S._states_and_territories_by_historical_population&amp;action=edit&amp;section=9" title="Edit section: 19002022, Federal Reserve economic data">
             <span>
              edit
             </span>

          <h2>
           <span class="mw-headline" id="Notes">
            Notes
           </span>
           <span class="mw-editsection">
            <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
             [
            </span>
            <a href="/w/index.php?title=List_of_U.S._states_and_territories_by_historical_population&amp;action=edit&amp;section=12" title="Edit section: Notes">
             <span>
              edit
             </span>
            </a>
            <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
             ]
            </span>
           </span>
          </h2>
          <link href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1011085734" rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style"/>
          <div class="reflist reflist-lower-alpha">
           <div class="mw-references-wrap mw-references-columns">
            <ol class="references">
             <li id="cite_note-1">
              <span class="mw-cite-backlink">
               <b>
                <a href="#cite_ref-1">
                 ^
                </a>
               </b>
              </span>
              <span class="reference-text">
               The
               <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/District_of_Columbia" title="District of Columbia">
                District of Columbia
               </a>
               is not shaded.
              </span>
             </li>
             <li id="cite_note-2">
              <span class="mw-cite-backlink">
               <b>
                <a href="#cite_ref-2">
                 ^
                </a>
               </b>
              </span>
              <span class="reference-text">
               Prior to 1920, territories in the
               <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Continental_United_States" title="Continental United States">
                continental United States
               </a>
               were generally included in the total population figure, but more far-flung territories were not.
              </span>
             </li>
             <li id="cite_note-3">
              <span class="mw-cite-backlink">
               <b>
                <a href="#cite_ref-3">
                 ^
                </a>
               </b>
              </span>
              <span class="reference-text">
               <link href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1133582631" rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style"/>
               <cite class="citation web cs1">
                <a class="external text" href="https://www.archives.gov/research/census/native-americans/1790-1930.htm" rel="nofollow">
                 "American Indians in the Federal Decennial Census, 1790-1930"
                </a>
                . U.S. Census Bureau
                <span class="reference-accessdate">
                 . Retrieved
                 <span class="nowrap">
                  August 27,
                 </span>
                 2021
                </span>
                .
               </cite>
               <span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.btitle=American+Indians+in+the+Federal+Decennial+Census%2C+1790-1930&amp;rft.pub=U.S.+Census+Bureau&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.archives.gov%2Fresearch%2Fcensus%2Fnative-americans%2F1790-1930.htm&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AList+of+U.S.+states+and+territories+by+historical+population">
               </span>
              </span>
             </li>
             <li id="cite_note-date-4">
              <span class="mw-cite-backlink">
               <b>
                <a href="#cite_ref-date_4-0">
                 ^
                </a>
               </b>
              </span>
              <span class="reference-text">
               Dates for the states are the dates they were admitted to the Union. Dates for the territories are the dates they were acquired by the United States (shown in italics). Date for the District of Columbia is the date the district was formed.
              </span>
             </li>
             <li id="cite_note-5">
              <span class="mw-cite-backlink">
               <b>
                <a href="#cite_ref-5">
                 ^
                </a>
               </b>
              </span>
              <span class="reference-text">
               The District of Columbia is not a state, but was created through the
               <a href="/wiki/Residence_Act" title="Residence Act">
                Residence Act
               </a>
               of 1790 from territory donated by Maryland and Virginia; however, the Virginia portion was
               <a href="/wiki/District_of_Columbia_retrocession" title="District of Columbia retrocession">
                retroceded
               </a>
               to the state in 1846.
              </span>
             </li>
             <li id="cite_note-6">
              <span class="mw-cite-backlink">
               <b>
                <a href="#cite_ref-6">
                 ^
                </a>
               </b>
              </span>
              <span class="reference-text">
               Previously a part of the
               <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Orleans_Territory" title="Orleans Territory">
                Orleans Territory
               </a>
               .
              </span>
             </li>
             <li id="cite_note-7">
              <span class="mw-cite-backlink">
               <b>
                <a href="#cite_ref-7">
                 ^
                </a>
               </b>
              </span>
              <span class="reference-text">
               Between 1790 and 1820, the
               <a href="/wiki/District_of_Maine" title="District of Maine">
                District of Maine
               </a>
               was part of the state of Massachusetts.
              </span>
             </li>
             <li id="cite_note-8">
              <span class="mw-cite-backlink">
               <b>
                <a href="#cite_ref-8">
                 ^
                </a>
               </b>
              </span>
              <span class="reference-text">
               Starting with the 1800 Census, Maryland donated territory to create the District of Columbia.
              </span>
             </li>
             <li id="cite_note-9">
              <span class="mw-cite-backlink">
               <b>
                <a href="#cite_ref-9">
                 ^
                </a>
               </b>
              </span>
              <span class="reference-text">
               Figures recorded for
               <a href="/wiki/Dakota_Territory" title="Dakota Territory">
                Dakota Territory
               </a>
               by the censuses of 1860, 1870, and 1880 are listed here as belonging to South Dakota.
              </span>
             </li>
             <li id="cite_note-10">
              <span class="mw-cite-backlink">
               <b>
                <a href="#cite_ref-10">
                 ^
                </a>
               </b>
              </span>
              <span class="reference-text">
               Vermont was enumerated in the 1790 Census but was only admitted as a state in 1791.
              </span>
             </li>
             <li id="cite_note-11">
              <span class="mw-cite-backlink">
               <b>
                <a href="#cite_ref-11">
                 ^
                </a>
               </b>
              </span>
              <span class="reference-text">
               Between 1790 and 1860, the state of West Virginia was part of Virginia. In addition, between the Censuses of 1800 and 1840, territory donated by the state of Virginia formed a portion of District of Columbia, but the land was returned in 1846.
              </span>
             </li>
             <li id="cite_note-12">
              <span class="mw-cite-backlink">
               <b>
                <a href="#cite_ref-12">
                 ^
                </a>
               </b>
              </span>
              <span class="reference-text">
               Between 1790 and 1860, the state of West Virginia was part of Virginia; the data for each state reflect the present-day boundaries.
              </span>
             </li>
             <li id="cite_note-13">
              <span class="mw-cite-backlink">
               <b>
                <a href="#cite_ref-13">
                 ^
                </a>
               </b>
              </span>
              <span class="reference-text">
               Not including the Virginia counties that formed the new state of West Virginia in 1863, but includes the enslaved population in the returned land that had been donated to form the District of Columbia.

Step 4: Convert the html tables into a python dictionary¶

Before we can think about how to extract what we need, we need to understand how tables are constructed in HTML...

Our goal is to associate a series of population values with each state, so that we can build a time series table across all three tables. Things to keep in mind while building our extract routine:

- We dont care about the admitted column 
- We want to remove the commas from the numbers so python interprets them as ints rather than strings 
- We want to remove the footnotes and links

Now, lets try to extract out our data

In [12]:
def rm_footnotes(s):
    """
    Removes any text after first '[' in string
    District of Columbia[1] -> District of Columbia"""
    # Your code here 
    return s.split('[')[0]

def clean_int(s):
    """Removes any commas or footnotes from string and converts to int.
       Returns zero for blank strings"""
    # Your code here 
    s = rm_footnotes(s)
    s = s.strip().replace(',','')
    return int(s) if s else 0
In [13]:
d = dict()

for table in tables:

    """Extracts population data for states from all tables in tables 
      and store it in single dictionary d """
    
    headrow = table.find("tr")
    
    col_names = [(idx,th.text.replace('\n','')) for idx,th in enumerate(headrow.find_all('th')) if th.text.strip().isnumeric()]
    # Makes list of tuples like this with idx and name for cols with years.
    # By using isnumeric, we only include columns are that are years. 
    # Result looks like this: 
    # [(2, '1790'), (3, '1800'), (4, '1810')]                     
    rows = table.find_all("tr")[1:]
    # List of rows in table excluding the header row 

    for row in rows:
        state_name = rm_footnotes(row.find('td').text).strip()
        # String of state name, with any footnotes removed 
        
        all_cells = [c.text for c in row.find_all('td')]
        # List of cell values for row, e.g.: 
        # ['Alabama', '1819', '\xa0', '1,250', '9,046' .. ] 
        
        existing_values = d.get(state_name,{})
        # Existing dict of values for given state 
        
        new_values = {year:clean_int(all_cells[idx]) for (idx,year) in col_names}
        # For cols listed in col_names, return dict of cleaned int values 
        # {'1790': 0, '1800': 1250, '1810': 9046...}
        
        existing_values.update(new_values)
        # Merge with existing dict for state 
        d[state_name] = existing_values
d

Step 5: Make a pandas dataframe from the dictionary¶

Now that we have all three tables in a cleaned dictionary form, with each state as a key, and time series for each sate (as another dict) as its value, it's simple to convert to a pandas DataFrame.

In [14]:
df = pd.DataFrame.from_dict(d,orient='index')

An alternative aproach -- Using pd.read_html() instead¶

In this particular situation, using Pandas built-in read_html function actually works pretty well, and would have saved us a lot of code above. However, not all datasets come in nicely formatted html tables, so its important to develop the skills to write a scraping routine from scratch from any type of html page (as we did above)

More info here: https://pandas.pydata.org/pandas-docs/stable/generated/pandas.read_html.html

In [16]:
pd.read_html(tables[0].prettify(),header=0, index_col=0)[0]

Step 6: let's plot our data!¶

In [17]:
df.T.plot(legend=None)
plt.ylabel("Population (Millions)")
plt.xlabel('Year \n\n (Every line represents the population for an individual state overtime)')
plt.title("US Population by State, 1790-2010")
Out[17]:

In [18]:
# let's look at just the 10 largest states (2010 population)
df.sort_values('2010', ascending=False)
largest = df['2010'].nlargest(10).index
df[df.index.isin(largest)].T.plot()
plt.legend(loc='center left', bbox_to_anchor=(1.0, 0.5))
plt.title("Population by State for 10 largest states, 1790-2010")
plt.ylabel("Population (Millions)")
plt.xlabel('Year \n\n (Every line represents the population for an individual state overtime)')
Out[18]:
Text(0.5, 0, 'Year \n\n (Every line represents the population for an individual state overtime)')

Perhaps it will be more interested to view as percentage of total US population, so we can see relative change overtime

In [19]:
import matplotlib.ticker as mtick
cols = df.columns
by_percent = df[cols].div(df[cols].sum(axis=0), axis=1).multiply(100)
by_percent[by_percent.index.isin(largest)].T.plot()
plt.legend(loc='center left', bbox_to_anchor=(1.0, 0.5))
plt.ylabel("Percent of total US population")
plt.xlabel("Year")
plt.title("Percentage of total US Population by State, 1790-2010")

# Make y-axis percentages 
ax = plt.gca()
fmt = '%.0f%%' # Format you want the ticks, e.g. '40%'
yticks = mtick.FormatStrFormatter(fmt)
ax.yaxis.set_major_formatter(yticks)
In [20]:
by_percent[by_percent.index.isin(largest)].T.plot(kind="bar",stacked=True)

plt.ylabel("Percent of total population")
plt.xlabel("Year")
